Government wants to curb torture of 'witches', publishes pamphlet
Women declared witches in Burkina Faso have several common characteristics.
Rather, they belong to the older generation, they cannot participate in work, for example, for health reasons, they are single and do not have children.
The one who "becomes" the witch is sent into isolation so as not to endanger the rest of the village.
"A man's fate is very rare."
“They don’t push young healthy women away either, because they help at work and give birth to children,” said the nun, who takes care of more than 100 women in a special home in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso.
The local government has now decided to take action against the unusual "social measures".
She has published an information booklet to help curb the witch hunt.
There's a catch.
"More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," Die Standard said in a statement.
Accusations of witchcraft are common in other African countries.
In Ghana, which borders Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week after being tortured by three women and two men, doused with kerosene and set on fire.
The BBC reported on the case.
The perpetrators say it was an unfortunate coincidence.
According to their version, an oil was ignited on the woman, which is used for ritual anointing.
He said the group was trying to "drive out the evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people regardless of the level of education achieved.
