Bakala's tenant: He's drowning in the stove, higher rent signed
An elderly man stepped out of the door of the client center of the company RPG Byty "uhlobaron" Zdeněk Bakala, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried a folder and in it new leases to three apartments: his own, his daughter and his son, who is in prison.
All three of them just got their rent up.
Instead of 3500 per month, the son will pay CZK 4100 for a 2+1 apartment of the second category from next year.
"And that's not hot water, and it has to be heated with kerosene," the man points his finger in his son's new contract, which he has full power to sign.
"But I signed it," he explains half angrily and half resignedly.
The civic association BytyOKD.cz, which has described the new lease terms as "incorrect and immoral", advises tenants not to sign the new contracts and to wait until December 7, when it will publish instructions on how to proceed against them.
But the man just waved his hand at it.
"One says it, the other it," he frowns.
Ostrava is becoming a big laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, the vast majority of apartments that still have non-market rent in the Czech Republic are waiting.
That’s why we decided to visit the “laboratory” in person.
Havířov RPG waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and on Tuesday at nine in the morning it is already full.
Right next to the door is a security guard from the security agency and a distress call.
"Hire 2011" is lit a special button on his touch screen.
One tap and a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
You will not even be able to read "157" and your number is beeping on the large display under the ceiling of the waiting room.
It's your turn in half a second.
After a while, an older married couple comes to ask about the rent, but the rush in the waiting room obviously does not concern the new leases at all.
Most people come to solve common problems as usual - requests for repairs, insurance claims and the like.
Letters with new leases have been delivered to mailboxes in Ostrava by most of the 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio since mid-November.
RPG Flats suggests in their letters to them a rent increase of 15 to 38 percent.
A special counter for new leases was opened at the client center on November 18.
"It's been running for over a week, so it's just in the run-up," workers behind the counter respond after a moment of hesitation when the client introduces himself as a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakala's former mining flats are a local hot topic.
Prior to the election, Deputy Speaker of the Parliament and Ostrava native Lubomír Zaorálek from ČSSD took it quite loudly, and even now it is full of local newspapers.
"Twenty years later, I want a new floor."
“They didn’t change a board in my bathroom,” said the man at the beginning.
Most of the time, pensioners come to see if they get a discount on rent if they sign in time, as the RPG in a special offer promises.
Half discount on February rent will also be given to other tenants who sign the new contract by December 15.
However, the "deregulation" counter in Havířov is not overloaded with questions.
"Of yesterday's 360 clients, there were only about 40 to 50 people here because of the 2011 rent," estimate the workers behind the counter.
RPG on the web and its boards proposes individual contract negotiation where it is needed.
However, if both parties do not agree on the lease, it will have to be determined by an independent court.
“This is not a threat, it is information about the only possible and entirely legitimate legal process,” RPG wrote on its website.
"No one will be able to sue here," one of the RPG Byty workers thinks, and the man on the street in front of the client center agrees with her in part.
“I have a 13,000 pension and 5,000 food left, and I don’t have time to judge,” he said.
But the workers are still worried.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaorálek tells them in the media not to sign, so people are probably waiting," he thinks.
Rent regulation ends in most of the Czech Republic with the New Year 2011 and according to RPG Byty, their increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rent is still not even the amount necessary for simple maintenance of the housing stock," recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of RPG Byty, that the neglected housing stock is the main reason, according to the homeowners, for the increase in rents.
In the five years between 2005 and 2010, RPGs could invest $4 billion in apartments, while in the four years from 2011 to 2014 it is expected to be $5.2 billion.
Meanwhile, a large screen hanging at the ceiling opposite the padded seats of the Havířov waiting room repeats some red highlighted information.
"The 2011 rent increase of 15% or less applies to 31,200 apartments, that's more than 90% of RPG apartments."
"And it will always be the most by 7.50 CZK per square meter and month," it appears on the screen.
With only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio, rents will increase by 38 percent.
"This is an increase from an extremely low amount of CZK 19.66 per square metre," the RPG points out.
For 2600 apartments, the rent will remain the same next year.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not drive out rents by leaps and bounds, but will be spread out over four to eight years.
In addition, it adds another commitment: all the money from the rent increase (see the graph) will put the company back into apartments, mainly in thermal savings - new windows and insulation.
They are to be given priority by the people who sign the lease increase agreement.
There is also a school, according to the architects.
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect that it would also hide a mini-kindergarten with all that goes with it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a pile of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, it can be visited by children of Arch.Design employees.
Arch.Design, a design-architectural company from whose studios a number of significant Brno buildings emerged, has been counting on space for its company mini-kindergarten since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
The company employs nearly 90 people, most of them baby boomers, and it was important for women designers and architects to be able to return to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of part-time work, the kindergarten is a benefit that Arch.Design offers its employees as part of a social program.
Builders and architects thus have the opportunity to combine demanding employment with child care.
The mini-kindergarten was created by Arch.Design employees themselves and with the support of the management they managed to obtain a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company mini-kindergarten is financed by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant funding (subsidies amounting to CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and provide qualified personnel and operation for two years.
After exhausting the financial subsidy (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to run a mini-kindergarten for 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of the project took one year and Economy Rating significantly helped with the application for the subsidy.
The care is provided by qualified staff, the children are cared for by a nurse and a kindergarten teacher all day long, so children without age restrictions can go to kindergarten, but most of them are older than 3 years.
Because it is a "mini-kindergarten", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but there will be more during the day.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of the parents, and the children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten, regardless of the hierarchy of the position in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the program content in the mini-kindergarten is comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with a quality education - from basic learning to preparation for school desks, the English language is also taught.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of young children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check on their child at any time, and there are no stressful situations with delayed picking up children from kindergartens away from the parents' workplace.
Parents are more productive with their working hours.
It is no wonder that there is a naturally loyal employee-employer relationship.
Arch.Design is one of the Czech companies that offer a significant benefit in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this program has strengthened personnel marketing.
The House of Bones continues to fascinate even after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the backbone of a dinosaur, and the balconies are open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Thanks to its organic shapes, the house has earned the nickname House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, tile and mosaic fragments, a facade resembling scales and ubiquitous soft curves are all typical of the Art Nouveau of Antoni Gaudí.
The facade of the house plays out dream lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
Detailed observation shows the geometry, rhythm and precisely thought-out order.
At night, the entire facade of the houses sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the brilliance of colors is even more enhanced.
The winding and twisting of the shapes appears equally in the interiors.
Wood in waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, peepholes and moldings.
House Batlló, which stands in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was created by the reconstruction of the house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sal Cortes.
Reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old structure and building an entirely new one, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper redevelopment.
The apartment house Casa Batlló was not designed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
It was designed by architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his design board that decorations were created for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaics on the facade.
Many other artists and artists have also worked on the facade.
The joint work on the design of the Casa Batlló house started a successful collaboration between Jujol and Gaudí.
Jujol was involved in the construction of Gaudi's Casa Milá and the Park of Guell, which contains Gaudi's other works.
From the locals, the house soon after its completion earned the nickname "House of Bones" due to its organic shapes.
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it "the yawning house".
It is also said that the sword of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted at the top of the structure.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Their 45-degree inclination may seem bizarre.
In the creation of Gaudí, he absolutely did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not let them bind him.
At the beginning of the construction, he received a building permit from the city, but the data on the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, the city council was horrified by the result and asked for correction.
For example, the council was bothered by the fact that the building also encroached on the pillars of the public sidewalk.
On the contrary, only fifteen days after the appeal of the municipal district, Josep Batlló requested (and successfully obtained) permission to lease the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social salon and on the third floor a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house intersects the staircase, through which you can climb to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening lounge doors, and the larger company can communicate with each other comfortably, without at the same time retaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new facade, the house with Gaudí’s reconstruction also received an unconventional roofing and two extra floors.
Gaudí’s play with the light, blue and white glazed tiles facing the inner courtyard and skylights is also impressive.
The game of two colors gives maximum light on all floors of the house.
Simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which in turn absorbs the sun's rays.
The Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and opulent apartment open to the public.
The owners decided to take this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the one hundred and fiftieth anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They stayed with the tours because they found it to be a very profitable business and in addition, they expanded the tours to include common and attic spaces, including a roof terrace.
The entrance fee to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes have a 20% discount.
The amount greatly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to experience the true atmosphere of a house with dragon turrets, you need to quickly make friends with one of the residents of the apartment building and visit it right at home.
How to choose a mattress and grate: women have different requirements than men
Not a flashy bed frame, but the quality of the sleeping area, that is, the mattress and the grate, give the basis for a really good bed.
However, they must be harmoniously complemented to suit a particular user.
When choosing, a lot of things are decided, from weight, height, age, health and gender of the owner.
Also important is the type of interior into which the mattress and grate are made.
Typical example?
For example, latex mattresses are not suitable for weekend cottages where they do not regularly heat up, because they "warm up" more slowly.
In addition, they have a significantly higher weight than a standard polyurethane mattress.
However, it is necessary to turn them regularly.
If they don’t have a lot of air ducts in the core, and they’re still lying on a solid board, they’re retaining moisture: There could be mold underneath.
Habits also determine the choice.
Those who have spent a long time abroad, where very high mattresses with a softening layer are often used, will hardly feel good on a low and hard surface.
"I hope all the hockey players who were coming back from the NHL complained to me that they weren't going to sleep here."
