Domestic manufacturers use, for example, foam Eucatherm C or Twinsaver and so on.
More and more parents want to monitor people, so they want to protect their children
More and more people are worried about their child being watched by GPS.
The system originally created for searching for cars can also track the movement of people, and thus help in such cases as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anna Janatkova.
The device is now about the size of a matchbox, but soon it can only be as big as a watch.
Many people were frightened by the case of the missing Anna and began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even at the expense of their privacy.
“We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying, but another means to reduce the likelihood that some tragedy will happen,” said Petr Pilin from Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices to the Czech market.
"I admit that in some cases such devices can be misused, for example when they are put in a bag for someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case."
“Most customers actually buy it for security reasons,” Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if the child does not want to wear anything similar, he will just get rid of it.
“Even very young children show a lot of creativity in how to intentionally lose things when they don’t want to be in control.”
"Big expectations were raised by mobile phones, which can be turned off just like these tracking devices," Bočková said.
It is also questionable whether such a device would really help in the event of an attack.
"When it comes to an upcoming kidnapping, the perpetrator practically always ensures that the child does not carry any electronics that could reveal his or her location."
"It's a phone now."
"When tracking devices begin to expand, they will look for them as well, as their sale will certainly be supported by massive advertising."
“In that case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police,” she says.
However, he admits that a similar device can help in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, even if the tracking device is destroyed immediately after an attack, its presence can help.
"The device can be set to periodically send the location after a certain period of time."
"If it is damaged, at least the last position of the person concerned will be available."
"More expensive devices also have built-in tiltometers, so even if a person just slipped and remained motionless, the device immediately sends a warning with the location," says Čech.
According to him, a similar service can be carried out by smart mobile phones with navigation, where it is enough to upload special software.
The problem with current tracking units is that they are either devices similar to matchbox-sized pendants or smaller mobile phones.
They are always at risk of losing it.
According to Pilin from Macro Weil, the device is now being tested to look like a regular digital watch.
"This will have the greatest advantage in that the potential aggressor may not recognize the tracking device at all."
"Or he'll recognize them after a while and that can give the police extra time," he adds.
Whether the trackers are developed into bracelets or pendants, they will still use the same technology that is used to monitor cars.
This is a combination of GPS location (which uses conventional auto-navigation) and the mobile phone function that reports the current position of the car.
The army has incendiary cords that would encircle the Czech Republic. But it will only last two years
The Czech Army has purchased 445 kilometers of cords to detonate explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defence delivered 224 kilometres of cords to the warehouses.
