Longer index finger than ring finger means lower cancer risk
Men who have a index finger longer than the ring finger are at less risk of getting prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British Cancer Journal.
It may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60,” said Ros Eeles, a professor at the University of Warwick’s Institute for Cancer Research.
The finger could help determine which men should be screened for prostate cancer, especially in combination with genetic risk or other threatening factors such as family health burden, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in the UK followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and over 3,000 healthy men at the same time.
More than half of the participants in the study had a index finger shorter than the ring finger.
They were as likely to have prostate cancer as those with 19% fingers the same length.
However, those with index fingers that were longer than the ring finger had a 33 percent lower risk, compared to 87 percent for men under 60.
The length ratio of the two fingers - formed in the prenatal period - seems to reflect the different levels of sex hormones to which the baby is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone promotes the growth of prostate cancer.
Professor Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told the Czech News Agency that he was familiar with the study, but that he did not seem to have "completely proven" the relationship between finger length and cancer.
