The Common Practice of Democracy
The promotion of democracy in Latin America is growing, as is the promotion of private enterprise.
Crime is of greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is considered by many regions to be more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of a recent Latino-Barometro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist magazine.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it can track changes in attitudes across the region.
In this year’s survey, which took place in September and early October, two related things dominate.
The first is that Latin America is in a rather cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy in several countries on the Pacific Rim in South America has increased significantly (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% that year.
It also rose in Mexico, where the economy was recovering after a deep decline in production last year.
But only about half of those polled in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous regions, are convinced Democrats, which pulls back the regional average (see Chart 2).
About 44% of respondents across the region said they were satisfied with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same number as last year, but a big increase compared to 2001 when it was 25% (Graph 3).
Roughly 34% said they trust the assembly in their country and 45% trust the government, again the same numbers as last year, but a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
A decade ago, the economic crisis undermined democracy in Latin America.
The support was created during the global financial crisis probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social security network has helped protect poor people.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty rose only marginally in 2009 and fell again this year to 32%.)
However, the mood varies from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil’s strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and the state of violent crime worsened.
For only the second time since surveys began to be conducted, more respondents across Latin America see crime rather than unemployment as the most important issue (see Chart 5).
Roughly 31% say that either they or their close relatives became victims of crime last year, but this is a decrease compared to 38% last year and is also the lowest figure since 1995.
More robust economic performance is reflected in increasing support for private business and the market economy: approximately 71% of respondents across the region say that private business is essential for development, this percentage has risen from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, this percentage has risen from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela share the same view (and 80% support private business there), although their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is the leading country in the region, as mentioned by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, compared to 11% last year).
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, with Venezuela enjoying success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic, and Nicaragua.
