The discovery of a strange bacterium that may use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the scope for searching for new life forms on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth, claiming that it is a sign that life has options that stand outside the main elements that were previously considered and fundamental.
"This organism has a dual ability."
"It can grow either through phosphorus or arsenic."
"This is a very strange fact, but it is not proof that it is some form of truly 'alien' life," said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report, which appeared in an online issue of the journal Science on Thursday.
For a long time, six main elements were considered necessary for life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, scientists have found that bacteria discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue growing after phosphorus is substituted for arsenic.
"You'll start to wonder what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
This finding is significant for the search for life beyond Earth, because researchers need to be able to recognize life and know what life might look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, the news report published to be discussed, which did not reveal the details of the find, has sparked widespread speculation on the Internet that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
That is not the case.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to use other elements to drive biochemistry and that a set of elements that we consider 'standard' may not be as absolutely necessary for life," explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element by another element in the basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't a random find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it exhibits high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she considered that a microbe that is exposed to both elements may be able to replace one another.
"Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus."
"As a result, organisms can find it very difficult to separate these elements from each other."
"However, arsenic is so different that, like phosphorus, it doesn't work. When it gets into the body, it starts working in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better under the action of phosphorus, but since they can also survive with arsenic replacement, the possibility increases that the life form that uses arsenic may occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, stated that the idea of arsenic, which could be replaced with phosphorus, is not new, but there has never been an example on which to prove this fact.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, so scientists speculated it may have been used by earlier life forms.
"This suggests that there may have been other ways to create life, not just the way it formed in the early Earth period," said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
