How to interpret this movement?
Let it be said in advance that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another point in the complicated process of redefinition of the euro.
And here, Germany has a radically new vision of what its future is supposed to be, countering the idea of upholding the old traditions held by a large part of the other members.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong eurozone, which would include Germany, but also, for example, Austria and the Netherlands, while the southern states would leave the currency zone.
The second is a return to the mark - although now it may seem like science fiction, this version has wide public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option, according to the German proposals, is to redesign the euro with more macroeconomic oversight, budgetary austerity, fines for offending states, possible deferrals of payments for some of them, and an extension of the possible costs of regulation to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for quite some time, so there is no room for the dials now.
First, when the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission incited deficits in 2009, the German government pulled constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of a contradiction between what Germany thought was right (plans for fiscal austerity and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The Central European country showed the second when Merkel painfully delayed decisions to save Greece.
It was already the subject of sharp criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion, which was also published, were strongly opposed to the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel has once again emerged with a clear stance, demanding to reform the European Union’s conventions so as to allow for the rescue of a member state and, at the same time, for private creditors to be obliged to bear part of the costs.
This opinion was interpreted as anti-European, as it precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, albeit in a somewhat softened form, has been approved, and we should follow the Union reform process over the coming months, which should make these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it tells all of us that, although measures now need to be taken, with which it seems to disagree too much, from that date on, the old functioning of the euro will end.
The year 2013 will mark the birth of a new currency zone in which breaker states will be severely sanctioned and may be forced to announce a deferral of payments, and the private sector will also have to bear part of the costs.
Germany is telling us that we must take a strict path of growth, with increased savings and investment, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital buffers.
They simply do not want to tolerate another debt- and building-based option, with huge balance-of-payments gaps like the one that reigned in the boom years of Spain’s growth.
The offer is clear.
