Fints like Alonso and Ramos in the match against Ajax show wit not intent to escape punishment.
The alleged expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on 23 November has caused a sea of ink to be written about whether or not this is unsportsmanlike behaviour and whether UEFA should eventually punish the two footballers.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (who had their team clearly won) the named players, one by one, deliberately lost time at the time when the foul was supposed to be played to provoke the referee, and he showed them a second yellow card.
In this way, both players will meet the prescribed penalty in the following match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid finishing in their group lead - and will be able, stripped of their cards, to proceed to the next stage.
In the end, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee awarded coach José Mourinho a two-game penalty, and guilty players were fined.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, rules that are unwritten, but are watched.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that Real Madrid (which boasts generosity and honor in its anthem, and which has already fined its players for similar acts) and, apparently, also due to the dramatization led by Mourinho, which adds another episode to its long history of comedian and provocateur.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this kind of conduct, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether there is a circumvention of the law in these acts; indeed, these are actions respecting the rules of sport, the meaning of which, of course, seems to be trying to get around.
It is discussed what kind of damage such actions cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the essentials of sportsmanship is the physical integrity of the opponents, which was not violated in these cases, so there was no violent game.
Another of these essentials characterizing pure play is to avoid players having an advantage over the opposing team due to their offense - which also did not happen here.
Thus, the paradox of the action of Real Madrid players is the fact that what we normally describe as a ruse or circumvention of the law did not occur, that there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid sanctions, but that this behavior should be as visible as possible in order to receive a penalty.
They waited and gladly received the punishment.
Another question, however, is how the culprits will benefit from their deliberate misdemeanor.
Here it is necessary to state that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that he will not achieve any benefit in the current match, because the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And this is not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously lies in the fact that players start the next stage of the Champions League without cards, which could threaten their participation in a future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, i.e. at first glance the team can be eliminated, and besides this, the players will be penalized by this action, and move to the second round of cards, in which one card less than in the first round is enough to be eliminated.
So how the rounds will go on, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations do not go against the spirit of sport, which includes making strategic decisions that will enable maximum benefit within the rules.
in the case we are dealing with here, the players did not aim to avoid punishment (which would be a clear case of circumventing the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without evading or fleeing punishment.
Although the line between wit and circumvention of the rules is not quite clear, I believe that in this case it was definitely wit.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because it was two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the instructions to provoke them were carried out from the leadership.
Harming sports principles with these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
The battle of offers to organize Christmas parties in Barcelona
The calendar dictates an avalanche of reservations on December 16 and 17 this year.
There is a rapidly increasing number of celebrations paid by employees themselves who want to spend between 20 and 30 euros.
Like Turkish honey or lotteries, with the advent of December, the pre-Christmas parties come again, which still act as an oxygen bomb for restaurants and leisure facilities in Barcelona, but thanks to the crisis have resulted in a fight to win clients by lowering prices: almost everyone wants to spend 20 to 30 euros for food, the surveyed entrepreneurs and associations from this sector agree.
To complete the complicating numbers, the calendar concentrated this year (when Christmas Day fell on Friday) on the week of December 13, creating an avalanche of bookings for peak days (16th and 17th), while there was almost no traffic the previous week.
As has been the case since 2008, when the lean years began, there are many companies that have canceled collective parties for budgetary reasons.
In order not to abandon traditions, many employees pay for parties out of their own pockets.
Regardless of the situation, many are demanding prices at the limit, according to Gaieta Farras, president of the association of restaurants Gremi de Restauració de Barcelona.
A representative of the patronage of restaurants does not dare to predict what the celebrations will be this month.
"People will think twice before making a reservation."
“They want to go out, but they are cautious when it comes to the topic of prices,” he adds.
Stores will go well for those “who offer quality and good service at a reasonable price”, he says, reminding that thanks to the crisis, customers tend to go down a notch and most customers now want to spend around 25 euros.
A survey at various facilities shows that the biggest onslaught of booking requests is for the evening of December 17.
The Soteras Group is reporting a real boom of bookings for this Friday, with most requests being for spends of up to 30 euros, adapted to the menus on offer, whose total prices range from 25 to 30 euros.
In another important company, Andilana, which has 16 facilities in the city (Hostal de la Rita, Market, La Fonda and others), the peculiarity of this year’s calendar has brought more early bookings since the beginning of November.
“We have made both possible and impossible in order to maintain last year’s prices, and our currency, which everyone should choose from, ranges from 19.95 to 30 euros,” they say.
In the AN Group, which includes El Mussol, Attic, QuQu and a total of 23 businesses, they remain optimistic after seeing growth in profits since the second half of the year and having fairly solid prospects for Christmas sales.
The company’s sources point out that December 18 will also be a busy day as pre-Christmas celebrations between friends take place.
They added a Christmas menu to their six group menus, with a budget of 30 euros or more, as they noticed a tendency for guests to spend 10% more in exchange for other items such as cava (Spanish sparkling wine).
They have also noted that companies are already emerging that are again inviting their employees, and the size of the groups seems to be slightly larger.
Fecasarm’s vice president (which includes institutions such as Barcelona’s Association of Bars, Restaurants and Leisure Centres) Enric Goma believes he is beginning to see the end of the tunnel, claiming that the number of bookings has “recovered”, although clients are “contracting to the maximum”.
This impression did not subside even during the Christmas celebrations, no matter who paid, he points out.
Pakistan's nuclear program has caused widespread unrest in the United States.
Islamabad is producing nuclear weapons “at a faster rate than any other country.”
Wikileaks documents confirm links between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the U.S. Embassy in Pakistan and the U.S. State Department published by Wikileaks confirms the extraordinary unease that the Pakistan nuclear program is fueling in Washington.
In addition to the clarifying and significant details they offer regarding the content of communications and the ideas of North American diplomacy representatives in Islamabad, these documents reveal that cooperation between the two states in terms of nuclear security, instead of increasing, is "on the decline", and that this unstable Asian country produces "more nuclear weapons than any other state".
The peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program - that its weapons are not assembled, but stored piecemeal to make it more difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack - is one of the main reasons for Washington's vigilance.
This is calculated by Ambassador to Pakistan Anne W. Patterson in one report prior to the visit of then-National Security Advisor James Jones: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to Taliban-controlled territory, the alleged dispersal of nuclear materials, and the vulnerability of the transport of atomic materials".
The increased number of people associated with nuclear arsenals and the missile program is no longer only observed by the US, but also by Russia, as a spreading and giving reason to be on the lookout.
“Pakistan has had to hire personnel with a strict religious faith to protect its nuclear facilities; due to the decline in education and culture, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people to work in nuclear or missile programs,” Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev told a meeting with his US counterparts.
The biggest news of the documentation published by Julian Assange’s server is the increasingly reduced cooperation between the US and Pakistan on the topic of nuclear proliferation and the increased pace of Pakistan’s production of these weapons.
A cable issued by the embassy in May, which qualifies communication with Pakistan as "frustrating", claims: "Transparency often does not exist; offers of assistance remain unanswered or are rejected".
Peter Lavoy, a national intelligence official for South Asia, said: “Despite economic disaster, Pakistan produces nuclear weapons as quickly as any other country in the world.”
Ambassador Petterson also asks Washington to "make very clear" that "Pakistan's military must put an end to tacit support for terrorist groups" during the visit of General Ashfaq Kayani's army chief.
Wikileaks boss hunt
Obama appoints a senior counter-terrorism official to avoid new leaks.
Interpol is issuing a "red alert" to track down and determine where Assange might be.
Everything about Wikileaks and its founder Julian Assange is a complicated labyrinth where it is hard to be sure of the facts.
Interpol yesterday announced an “extraordinary call,” a red notice, to “localize and track Assange’s movements.”
However, this is not a typical detention order.
Besides, this challenge is not new, but dates back to November 20.
And it has nothing to do with the latest leak of more than a quarter of a million diplomatic documents, but with the allegations of sexual abuse that the Australian faces in Sweden.
Mark Stephens, a lawyer for Wikileaks, said: “The police know where and how to get in touch with Mr. Assange.”
It was November 20 when the International Police Corps, based in Lyon, France, issued this order at the request of Sweden, but it did not publish it until yesterday, when it received permission from the Swedish authorities.
In this situation, 188 Interpol countries have been instructed to identify or locate Assange "with the aim of placing him under temporary detention and extraditing him."
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of the person subject to the red alert, many member states, as the organization has explained, consider the red alert to be an enabler of the arrest - this must be ensured by the national police force - especially if the states have a bilateral agreement on the extradition of detainees, as is the case in Sweden and England, where Assange is likely to be located.
The move scandalized Assenge’s lawyers, who published a letter yesterday declaring that the 39-year-old founder of Wikileaks has shown a willingness to answer questions from Swedish authorities via videoconference.
They also recall that Assenge sought and subsequently received permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor of his case, which they compare to the legendary Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, the head of Stalin's security.
"This is a hunt and not a legal pursuit," the letter states.
While the whole world searches for him - and from Australia his mother defends her son's innocence - Assange remains in an unknown place, but he does not remain silent.
On Monday, he interviewed Time magazine’s editor-in-chief via Skype, demanding the resignation of U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If it turns out that she was responsible for ordering U.S. diplomats to conduct espionage at the United Nations in violation of international conventions that the United States has signed, she should resign," he said.
His opinion was rejected yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who qualified the demand for resignation as "ridiculous and absurd".
"I'm not entirely sure why we should care about the opinion of the individual who runs the website," he told CNN.
Obama himself has commissioned a senior counter-terrorism official, Russell Travers, to prevent further document leaks.
President Barack Obama’s intention to stop adding importance to Assange contrasts with the views being voiced by conservative politicians and commentators these days.
Peter King, a member of Congress who will chair the House of Commons National Security Committee from January, asked the State Department to explore the possibility of including Wikileaks as a terrorist organization "so that anyone who would contribute or otherwise assist them can be intervened and prosecuted."
Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian Prime Minister Stephen Harper, said Assange should be "killed," which he subsequently had to retract.
"Obama should put a bounty on him or use an unmanned aircraft or something like that".
Who did not apologize was Mike Huckabee, a Baptist priest, former Arkansas governor, and a possible candidate for president.
"Whoever's in government, whoever's responsible for the leak has committed treason, and any punishment other than execution would be too lenient," he said.
Puigcercós seeks peace in ERC by "squinting" at Caroda adherents
The Republican leader will allow the party to vote in secret.
Huguet proposes a more plural executive and an end to the meeting system.
Joan Puigcercos seems to have found a recipe to fight the already multiple internal revolts in the ERC ranks, to no avail due to the loss of 11 MPs and half the votes.
The party leader is aware that his resignation gesture seems inadequate to the supporters of former leader Josep Lluís Carod-Rovira, and he also knows that the sector’s influence is now as weakened as its leader himself, and that he absolutely cannot make him worry as much as he did with other defunct currents.
That is why the leader of the Left will try to win new criticisms through winks that will help him to defend himself in municipal elections.
First, Puigcercos announced yesterday that more than 200 members of the national committee would be able to make a secret statement about his stay in office.
Using ballots, not raising your hand.
If Carod supporters want to give the president a criminal vote, they will be able to do so without fear of reprisals.
In fact, the boss wants to avoid the division and submission of his person.
in several interviews he claimed that he would not consider himself confirmed with half the votes and one extra, but added, without specifying the percentage, that there would also not be a good result "in Bulgarian".
Supporters of Carod demand that the president do more than make his position available - a gesture that has no weight, as Puigcercos controls the largest body at conventions.
But since they don’t have a majority enough to force the resignations, they will try to make the executive resemble the plan from now until May.
As a result, they expect to participate in the drafting of a strategic reorientation document, which will be put to the vote of the National Council on the 18th of the month.
Their goal is to support Puigcercós in exchange for him promising to move Congress as early as fall 2011.
The leader of the ERC said that "multiplicity" harms stability, and that his goal is for the organization to be able to wash its dirty laundry behind closed doors once and for all.
In this context, the article that current advisor Josep Huguet signed on his blog seems to be significant.
After taking into account Puigcercos's ideologue, this innovation advisor took for granted that the leader would be confirmed "in exchange for several goals".
And he named five of them, of whom two stand out.
The first is to "re-compile" the executive to represent at least 90% of the members, which means also include new faces who are from a sector leaning towards Carod.
The second goal can be great news.
Huguet suggests that the ERC should put an end to meeting-making as a mechanism for functioning.
And so he fights for reform of the statutes, so that congresses can be held through delegates chosen by vote.
Ending the model of the meeting system, an exception in the Spanish political party system, is the intended goal of the Puigcercós team, which has been fighting in this direction since the last two conventions.
However, the convulsive assembly of 2008 decided that the meeting must be considered at a special congress on the reforms of the statutes.
This matter is still unresolved, as the situation within the party has discouraged resolution of the matter.
Now, without the looming critical sectors, it might be a good time to revisit the matter and try to close it once and for all.
23 killed in November; 390 in 2010
According to the daily MILENIO, Mexico recorded a decrease of 4 cases compared to 2010.
In November, 23 people were killed in Mexico, four fewer than in the previous month, according to the MILENIO newspaper.
Among the killings are cases of three women and the discovery of a pair of separate bodies in the Valley of Mexico.
In the penultimate month of the year, there are a total of 390 homicides in Mexico, probably related to organized crime.
Among the cases stands out the finding of a corpse in San Diego de los Padres Cuexcontitlán, in the district of Toluca.
The victim suffered at least three gunshot wounds, as well as a grace-to-the-head blow, and had her arms and legs handcuffed with a rope.
The next day, a body was found in a trunk that was stored in the vehicle's luggage compartment above Mixtecas Street, in the Santa Cruz Acatlán Colony, in Naucalpan County.
Early on the morning of Thursday, November 4, cooperatives discovered a body bearing signs of torture and at least three fatal shots to the chest near the Tenango-Ixtapan de la Sal highway in a section of Villa Guerrero County.
Next to the body was a report signed by the suspected criminal organization La Familia Michoacana.
A day later, a 50-year-old man was murdered in Nezahualcoyotl by eight gunshots after he came out of his house and wanted to start collecting garbage.
On November 7, two victims aged 30 in the San Pedro Xalaxtoc colony, in Ecatepec County, were killed by a gunshot to the head.
In Chalco, on a remote road in the colony of El Naranjo, the body of a man shot in the forehead was found, and under the body was found a shell casing from a gun of caliber 25.
In Ecatepec were found parts of the human body in a sewage canal in the colony of Playa Golondrina.
Rescue services carried out a thorough search for other parts of it, but did not find them.
Residents of Tepotzotlan reported finding the body with their hands tied back and their heads wrapped around the Pena Colorado site.
The man had a gunshot wound to the back of his neck.
In the middle of the month, the murder of two men who were wrapped in bedding and left in the boot of a vehicle in Villas de la Hacienda in the Atizapán de Zaragoza district was reported, and death threats were also found among the victims.
A day later, a cardboard box containing a human head was found in the Valle de los Reyes colony in Los Reyes County.
In a nearby colony, the rest of the body was found, wrapped in a black plastic bag, with a message from El Incorregible.
On the 17th, two dead women wrapped in bed linen were found in the settlement of Zoquiapan in the Ixtapaluca district, and the next morning, a man killed in Huixquilucan wrapped in a yellow-blue sheet, which was tentatively identified as Mario Ríos according to a report left by the killers near his body.
In Ixtapaluca, a lifeless woman was found in the San Francisco Acuautla settlement with two wounds to the back of her head.
A tattoo of the sacred figure of Santa Muerte was discovered on the skin of the woman, as well as necklaces with her effigy.
At the end of the month, the body of a man with at least a third gunshot wound and a report signed by a criminal group was found in the village of Zinacantepec.
Two days later, the bodies of two men who had their heads wrapped in tape were found and a report was also found in the municipality of Puente de Piedra, in Santiago Tepatlaxco.
Among the victims, the report was probably written by one of the criminal organizations, which said, "This will happen to those who do not conform."
Two bodies were found in Ecatepec that bore signs of torture and had limbs tied up inside an abandoned taxi outside the Justice Center in the San Agustin Colony.
On the last day of the month, the remains of two men were found in Los Reyes La Paz and Nezahualcóyotl districts.
The first was beheaded and found in the colony of Cuchilla Ancón and was wrapped in black plastic bags, tied with tape, and had a message left with him; while the second was martyred and was found in a plastic wrapper in the streets of Colonia Juárez.
Agents found a note along with it.
China sets goals to reduce greenhouse gas emissions
At the UN climate change conference COP16, the country’s representative assured that his country has made extraordinary efforts to reduce its carbon footprint, and stated that he insists on his promise to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45% by 2020.
China will keep its pledge to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45% in 2020, Su Wei, the country’s representative at the UN climate change conference, said.
In his first public speech at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, Su Wei assured that his country has made an enormous effort to reduce its carbon footprint and transform its industry.
He said his country has already invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions over the past four years.
But he said China would not change its goals and would continue to work with the international community on the matter.
China’s strategy on climate change is divided into four areas: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
He explained that progress has already been made on all of these issues, including last year’s approval of a new energy law that includes proposed targets to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
He also stressed that in China, federal authorities worked in coordination with provincial and local authorities to achieve their goals in terms of energy saving, energy efficiency and emission reduction.
In addition, he said, various multi-year plans are underway or have already been completed, funded by both the Chinese and other governments.
For example, it is the Energy Efficiency Programme, which has been in place for the past five years and which has received investment from the UN, the government and private initiatives.
A provincial climate change project is also underway, as well as a project to replace fluorescent lamps with energy-saving light bulbs and a mitigation and adaptation project.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the country’s expert adviser on climate change, assured that China’s efforts were greater than generally thought.
For example, greenhouse gas emissions per capita account for 6 tons in China, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9% of the historical share of emissions.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in terms of energy use - for example, it has increased energy efficiency by 20% over the last five years and expects to make further progress by 2020, he added.
Espino: César Nava
The National Leader of the PAN (Partido Acción Nacional) party stated that the former chairman of this party is entitled to demand his law from the National Order Commission.
The PAN party's national chairman, César Nava Vázquez, has assured that the expulsion of Manuel Espina Barrientos has been enacted, and that the party's former chairman is entitled to turn to the National Order Commission and demand his right.
In an interview that was taken before the state governor, Gabin Cué Monteagudo, objected, saying that the expulsion of Espin is in any case a decision taken at the local level.
"This is an autonomous decision by the Sonora Riot Commission."
"Mr. Espino has the right to address his case through a complaint to the National Council Order Commission in order to make a decision made by the competent authority," he added.
He further explained that now was not the time to think about 2012, and that he had never been to the negotiating table on the alliance's presidential candidacy.
Nava Vázquez expressed his belief that the PAN would come out of the internal elections held on the following 4 and 5 December, in which his successor would be elected, strengthened.
"This (2012 alliance) is a topic that has never been at the negotiating table, at least not yet, it was a local election intention that was successful and fulfilled its purpose," he said.
The chairman of the PAN said that 71 years of dialogue are behind his party, and therefore "we are not afraid of internal competition, on the contrary, we benefit from it and strengthen us", he added.
He said the committee could easily elect the best chairperson it deserves for the next three years, so he handed over the baton to "whom the committee will appoint."
"So I am absolutely calm and relaxed, and I am proud to hand over the office of the party chairman to any of the five."
He predicted that the party's rise in the last election in July would be reflected in future contests, although "there is not yet time to think about 2012".
"Now it is necessary to accompany Governor Gabin Cué in this task".
In this context, he stressed that the three governments, rooted in the alliances of Oaxaca, Pueble and Sinaloa, would constitute a flag and would be subject to observation throughout the country, as "many expectations and aspirations are placed in them, and I am sure Gabino will live up to those expectations".
When asked about President Felipe Calderón’s criticisms by the PRI (Partido Revolucionario Institucional) because of his four-year speeches, César Nava urged PRI members to think about the six-year terms of former presidents Ernesto Zedillo and Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
“If the PRI believes that the governments of Zedillo and Salinas were better than those of Fox and Claderon, then let them start defending them, let them come out of their shells,” he said.
He said the head of the federal executive has the right to express himself, as he did during a speech at the National Auditorium, because there is no gag or censorship in this country.
Obama launches Twitter bill to support undocumented students
“If you think the Dream Act approval is right, let your senators know and urge them to pass it,” the president tweeted.
President Barack Obama today, by posting on his personal Twitter account, joined a national mobilization in support of the Dream Act, which should legalize undocumented students.
"If you think the passing of the Dream Act is right, let your senators know and urge them to pass it," Obama tweeted.
His short report draws attention to an internet link to a more comprehensive document asking the public to contact senators immediately as a vote on the bill approaches.
"As the vote is expected to take place soon, now is the time to let your opinion be heard," he points out.
The report was released after 42 Republican senators threatened to block the passage of any law unless an extension to Bush-era tax cuts and government funding was approved.
Such a blocking, which was announced in a letter signed by 42 Republican senators, could affect the vote on the Dream Act and other projects, such as the ratification of a new treaty with Russia against nuclear proliferation, called START.
When asked about the Republican blocking of the Dream Act and other proposals, the presidential spokesman said he believed that once the fiscal issue was resolved, it would be possible to compile a calendar for the rest of the projects.
“I think there’s still plenty of time...”
"We all agree that we need to resolve the tax issue before the end of the year..."
I believe that we can reach an agreement on this at some point and then we can plan the order of the other issues," he said.
Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid announced Tuesday that he would call for a "closing debate" on the Dream Act, so a bill to legalize undocumented students could be voted on in the Senate starting next Thursday, though more likely next week.
A Senate bill would legalize about 800,000 young people who entered the United States before the age of 16, had resided in the country for the past five years, and were admitted to a higher education institution or the military.
However, supporters need 60 votes to approve the bill, which is why they need the help of several Republicans, so organizations of its adherents are conducting intense agitation to ensure that the bill is passed.
Democrats, the majority of whom support the Dream Act, have 58 seats.
However, at least one of them, Senator Ben Nelson of Nebraska, said he would vote against, and only one Republican, Richard Lugar of Indiana, expressed his support for the bill.
Therefore, supporters of the Dream Act need to win several Republicans in case other Democrats decide to reject the proposal.
Among the Republican senators with whom the supporters are negotiating the most are Maine Senators Olympia Snowe and Susan Colins, as well as outgoing Florida Senator George Lemieux, who added a mandate to Senator Mel Martínez.
Other Republicans who previously supported the Dream Act include Orrin Hatch of Utah and Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas, but said they would not support it next time.
Another Republican who supported the bill, John Mccain, has not yet made a statement.
Although the House of Representatives is leaning toward a different version, according to most analysts, the Dream Act will face the biggest hurdles in the Senate.
"Poner el dedo en la llaga" ("To put a finger into a wound") is the equivalent of the Czech word "to hit a nail on the head."
The second round of the Pleasure of Language cycle was a promenade where participants performed a literary gala performance
"I understand that with Sex in the language, but... Finger in the wound? What is expected of me?", asked writer Luisa Valenzuel, who was invited to open the second round of Pleasure in the Language, a cycle that celebrates literature written in the Spanish language, and whose question was used on this occasion as a subtitle (at another trade fair, she explained, they devoted themselves to the topic of Sex in the Language).
The finger in the wound "puts us in a tight spot", said the lovely Argentinean writer to the audience, composed mostly of young people, who met at the International Book Fair in Guadalajara to listen to this round table debate, moderated by Marisol Schultz and with the participation of Valenzuel, Sergio Ramírez, Mayra Monterrey and Luise Garcia.
Luisa Valenzuel read a text she dedicated to Gonzalo Celorio, which Schultz then called a great story, featuring Luisa in the first person as the protagonist, who, in search of knowledge, goes from doctor to doctor, from whom she does not get answers, although the clues of the same story do.
From the infectiousologist leaves convinced: "Patience is not my strong suit, maybe it will be my blow".
Finally, after frustration with a traumatologist who took her breath away in the middle of the journey but explained to her that the wound is not a scientific term, it is the psychoanalyst who reveals the secret: "the wound represents it really opened and the symbolic one is the scar".
The protagonist sighed slightly and concluded that "she only managed to learn so much about the wound that it is really open and that it does not exist", but she became convinced that pleasures and pitfalls in language must go hand in hand.
Writer Valenzuel played with both.
Nicaraguan Sergio Ramírez also spoke with a delightful narrative, which he called Praise of Invention, in which the finger in the wound is not named, but at one point appears.
with elements of magical realism tells of a famous witch who played the clouds, brought back people who had gone far, or corrected the virtue lost by one virgin, this narrative that then turned to speak America, a great novel in which from the beginning there was not missing his own chroniclers who told it, and here is quoted by the captain of the period, Bernal Díaz del Castillo, who criticizes the exaggerations of the narrative.
"Cervantes, who invented all of us, mocked the false testimony presented as real in the stories, but in no other way could he tell the story of America with a imagination that lacked even shame."
However, he stressed, "they are fools and liars who have more imagination" and just where reality and lie merge, where one no longer knows what from the story belongs to one group and what to the other, the fictional literature reaches its peak.
He calls it the “Cervantian tradition.”
"Thanks to his legacy, we have what we have."
Subsequently, Mayra Monterová emphasized and praised the diversity of interpretations made possible by the invitation to the International Book Fair with her talk Finger to the Wound.
The Cuban-Portorian writer pointed her finger at the great blow of social violence that runs through her country - and is shared by Latin America - and is the result of trade disputes and drug sales.
"I think good literature, good poetry and good songs conclude a silent compromise, which of course is not intended", she said after stating that the reality of the literature is a communication and dimension of the compromise that is being formed between the author and the readers - and in their "chemical reaction".
The evening concluded with the Spanish poet Luis García Montero, whose performance also emphasized "this finger in the wound of a writer bound by a writer".
He said that in a world that lives in haste, also in intellectual habits and the control of consciousness that overflows with dogmatisms, one forgets that "there's a little no behind every yes, and there's a little yes behind every denial".
“To be the master of our thoughts and reality we must color: and to color means many times to put a finger in the wound and bother those individuals who are much more comfortable, because they think in cartoons, in black and white, in fixed ideas and without coloration, and also to bother the authorities who prefer this black and white world,” he said to support the meaning of the writing.
Romano goes for his first title
Rubén Omar Romano has suffered three defeats in the final, both good and bad in his career, but he has already managed to achieve on three occasions in a crucial series.
In the Santos Laguna and Monterrey finals, there are also two different styles of techniques, teams that have a noticeable difference in results.
Rubén Omar Romano has suffered three defeats in the final, both good and bad during his career, but he has managed to achieve on three occasions on the decisive series, but until now he has left with no success, which is why this chance is extraordinary for him.
The Argentine had to settle for a silver medal, staying one step behind the winners and playing quaintly with the same team following the final.
The Santistic strategist reached his first final in the 2002 Apertura tournament when he held the reins of the Morelia club, with which he lost 4-2 overall against Toluca; then in the 2003 Clausura tournament he advanced to the decisive duel again and also lost it with a total score of 3-1, which was against the Rayados team.
Already with Santos Laguna in the 2010 Torneo Bicentenario, again against the "Devils" of Toluca, Rubén again suffered a defeat, although his team played against the "Smokers" (another nickname of the club Deportivo Toluca) after 210 minutes of play, he suffered a 2-2 turnaround, after a series of penalty shots he got into the advantage of three to one and had two chances to play.
Rubén has already lost two finals against the "Red Devils" of Toluca and one against Monterrey, his future rival, so he would like to avoid the same fate and get rid of the curse, so he can celebrate the title for the first time, although he says that for him the most important institution.
"I want to come out as a winner, I don't want to break the statistics, this is for the club, for the passion that I'm committed to, and the title would obviously be for me, but the first one is the most important," the coach said when asked about the numbers that speak against him in the final.
He has a vivid memory of the previous final, in which he has, as he confirms, learned a lot, "we learned the lesson that until the referee whistles the end, we can't celebrate, we have to be ready for action, as well as the players, because last time with two penalties, we were already ready to run out to celebrate, and I think we learned the lesson here until the match is over, we can't celebrate".
He is not concerned that this series could be decided in penalty shots, he trusts his players: "You never try to get a series of penalty kicks, you try to finish in normal time, but sometimes there is no other option and you need to be prepared for it, in the last tournament we were ready, unfortunately fate has prepared us for a bad move, perhaps because of the nerves or anxiety that we felt when the title was in our hands, but we lost it".
Romano has a chance in his hands to stop being the other and experience the fame brought by titles for the first time.
The United States changed the rules for issuing visas
People will need to contact the Visa Services Centres before interviewing the Consular Section; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa process at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will need to contact the Visa Services Centres (ASC for short) before interviewing the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will collect the applicant’s biometric information and these will be evaluated by the Consular Department prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including:
The total cost of the visa will be lower, you will no longer have to pay a fee for the appointment, the second for the processing of the application and another for the delivery of the document by the shipping service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee to cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases with applications (including temporary workers visas), and $390 for a visa for merchants and investors.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go through an interview with a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
As biometric information will be collected in the ASC, applicants who will require a second appointment with an interview at the Consular Department will spend less time there than in the past.
Likewise, those who apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra $26 service fee.
For more information about the new visa application procedure, please visit the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boltines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
NASA Announces Discovery of Extraterrestrial Life
The U.S. Space Agency has called a press conference tomorrow to present a discovery that could cause a breakthrough in the search for extraterrestrial life.
The United States National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) will announce tomorrow, Thursday, an astrobiological discovery that could confirm the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The discovery will be presented tomorrow at 1 p.m. by experts in astrobiology, a science that studies the origin, evolution, spread, and future of life in space, at a press conference at NASA headquarters in Washington.
When she invited journalists, NASA assured that it would present "a discovery that will cause a turning point in the search for extraterrestrial life", prompting speculation from experts from other countries.
The discovery could confirm the theory that there are other creatures besides us who live in inhospitable conditions that were considered uninhabitable, and who could represent the possibility that they will one day become intelligent creatures, such as humans, if the conditions in which they live improve.
It appears to be a microbe found at the bottom of Lake Mono in Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment that has been deemed too toxic for any form of life as the lake is rich in arsenic.
The creature somehow uses arsenic for its life, and it is this ability that increases the likelihood that similar life could exist on other planets that do not have the atmosphere that it is on Earth.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it will be proven that "there is another, second form of life, different from the one we know".
The space agency will announce the true impact of the discoveries at tomorrow's press conference.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who is studying the possibility of life on Mars; biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who is studying Titan (the largest moon of Saturn), with the prospect that its chemical composition is similar to that of Earth.
