Dupont
Quebec radio presenter Stéphane Dupont suffered a partial setback before the Canadian Broadcasting Standards Council (RRTV) due to controversial statements regarding social assistance and Haitians and, as well as harsh language during broadcasts.
The Radio and Television Broadcasting Council judges that Mr. Dupont and his group from CHOI 98.1 FM had the right to express their views, but some statements contained "inaccurate information about social assistance and inappropriate negative portrayals of Haitians of rude language that does not correspond to broadcasts broadcast during the day".
The Council also concluded that the discussions on suicide, including the transmission of the names of the two persons who took their own lives, did not violate the regulations for radio broadcasting.
The Broadcasting Council received several complaints regarding comments made during the broadcasts, aired between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was made after a complaint by the Joint Front of Social Support Recipients of Quebec.
The group complained that the amounts reported on the air were inaccurate.
Moderators must provide reliable information, not deceptive information.
As for suicide, moderator Stéphane Dupont thought that suicide was a gesture of desperation.
Most members of the commission concluded that the message being transmitted was such that suicide could not be understood as a solution to the problems of everyday life.
"The majority of the Commission believes that the disputed episodes of the broadcast of 'Dupont's midday news' have come across a delicate subject in an impartial and appropriate manner."
No reproach was made against him.
The latest controversy concerned statements that followed the earthquake in Haiti.
Thus, Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort embarked on a media shootout that provoked many reactions.
The moderator of CHOI stated that he did not send any donation to help Haitians because we cannot know for sure that the needy will actually receive the money.
The Commission considers that these comments were not unjustified, but that their cumulative effect creates an unduly negative image for Haitians.
"I have already atoned for my three-day reprieve of the matter."
"My file has been intact for one and a half years," the presenter said.
In all decisions, the Commission refuses to use harsh language in its broadcasts.
Anyway, the CHOI-FM radio broadcast worked "beyond its responsibilities".
For the station, which will, inter alia, have to announce these decisions once during the main broadcast within a period of three days, the consequences are minimal.
