$450 million without public tenders
Hydro-Québec has agreed to $450 million in contracts with engineering firms for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of more than 100 contracts is the consortium formed by BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which won the most important contract, the contract to manage the entire project for a total of $295 million without a public tender.
This consortium, named Énergie gérance, was authorized in 2004 in parallel with the selection of Hydro-Québec to entrust to the private sector its responsibility for the management of this major hydroelectric project worth $5 billion.
In early 2005, the consortium "Énergie gérance" won a lucrative contract without any announcement of a public tender.
For the Quebec side, a complaint against a consortium of businesses presents us with a serious problem of an ethical nature that risks eliminating competition and triggering price increases.
"It's a new way to implement collusion and liquidate competition."
"This means that people no longer make side deals in secret, they are now doing them openly," PQ MP Sylvain Simard told a news conference.
A little earlier, in the morning, M. Simard asked this question to the National Assembly, because he says he finds it hard to bear how the public interest can thus be sold.
The Secretary of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, objected in the afternoon, strongly denying that this contract was a collusion.
"I have my own way", she thundered, claiming that the PQ was "dishonest" and "lacked accuracy".
She said that "it would be the least I could do" that PQ would apologize.
The recipe for a consortium is common practice all over the world.
It is usually a limited-time alliance that allows two or more companies to pool their mutual expertise in order to respond to a call for bids for a complex project.
The Eastmain project is very complex due to the complexity of the work.
Construction is underway and must be completed by 2012.
However, the contract was awarded without competition being able to act; it was a trade.
It must also be admitted that the consortium formula is no longer an exception in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir revealed last week, the formula of engineering consultancy consortia is under investigation in the government.
If we move quickly through the register of Quebec companies, it will allow us to discover more than 200 consortia, some of which seem to have been created permanently.
This is how Dessau works in partnership with most of its major competitors; let’s name CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin and Roche and Tecsult.
Every combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to one and the same legal entity, and that is Dessau.
Regarding the Énergie Gérance consortium, Minister Normandeau underlined in particular the fact that "the territory of la Baie James is characterised by a particular dynamism of the workforce and that Hydro-Québec has been responding to it since the 1970s".
