The Global Roadmap for Lighting Restoration
The United Nations has proposed a plan to restore home lighting, shop lighting and industrial space in 100 countries in order to limit the greenhouse effect (GES), which corresponds to almost one-third of the additional limitation that must be achieved to stabilize the planet’s climate from now until 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to promote in Cancún to compensate for the lack of hard-to-fulfill commitments to reduction on the part of industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if we replace the incandescent bulbs that monopolize 50 to 70% of the market with fluorescent or, even better, electroluminescent light bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), a substantial amount of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet generated due to lighting would be eliminated.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That’s the equivalent of 70 percent of the world’s car fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, among them Canada, engaged in voluntary reduction plans that should allow GES global emissions to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But another 5 Gt will have to be subtracted from this balance in order to achieve a stabilization of climate warming to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 so that it can be ruled out from being out of control.
In hot bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat, and the rest, i.e. 5%, is the product of light.
With fluorescent lamps, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, and with new bulbs with DEL, we will reduce this consumption twice more.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL bulbs, which were introduced into Philips production this week - the company reportedly participated in the UN study - have an estimated lifetime of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a hot bulb, giving us an idea of a possible savings with a replacement plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have voiced reservations about fluorescent light bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless producers set up collection points.
However, as the report states, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a fluocompact light bulb, but rather thermal coal-fired power plants that emit many of the mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in hot light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these centers put 25,000 tons of mercury into circulation each year.
The report also detailed the gains that would be made from this international program by each country.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion a year by purchasing electricity and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants worth $2.5 billion.
