Vengeful hackers and industrious spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double meaning.
On the one hand, an obvious scandal is revealed, a scandal that appears to be a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens, and the press.
On the other hand, it speaks of profound changes at the international level, and anticipates a future dominated by regression.
But let's move on.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is a confirmation of the fact that every document compiled by the secret service (of any nation) consists entirely of press cuts.
The Americans’ “extraordinary revelations” about Berlusconi’s sex-lifestyle are heralded by what everyone has been able to read in any newspaper for months (all but the two Berlusconi’s own), and the infamous caricature profile of Gaddafi has long been the subject of sketches for cabaret artists.
The rule that secret documents can only consist of reports already known is fundamental in the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
When you go to a bookstore devoted to esoteric literature, you will see that each work repeats (about Graal, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Masons) exactly what has already been written in previous works.
Not only because the author of occult texts does not like to look for new information (he does not even know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who are engaged in occultism believe only what they already know and what confirms what they have already learned.
That's Dan Brown's mechanism of success.
The same goes for secret documents.
An informer is a lazy, lazy (or limited spirit) head of the secret services (and if he isn’t, he could be, I know, an editor in the Libération newspaper) who only considers what he admits to being true.
The highly classified information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy sent to the state department was the same one Newsweek had published the week before.
Why, then, has there been so much fuss about the revelations about these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every cultured person already knows, that embassies, at least since the end of World War II and since heads of state can make phone calls or fly off to dinner together, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representative exercises, have transformed into spy centers.
Any spectator watching movies about the investigation knows very well that it is only out of hypocrisy that it is seemingly ignored.
However, the fact that it is repeated publicly defames the duty of hypocrisy and casts a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can obtain the most highly classified information of the most powerful country in the world is a hard blow, not an insignificant one, to the prestige of this state resort.
The scandal affects both the victims and their "executors".
But let's move on from there to the profound truth of what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell's time, it was possible to embrace all power, like some Big Brother who controlled every movement of his people.
Orvell's prophecy has been proven ever since, thanks to the ability to control every movement through the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway used and so on, the citizen became a complete victim of a wreath of power.
But when we demonstrate, as is happening now, that even the “graves” with the most secret information of the powerful cannot resist the intervention of some hacker, the control message ceases to be one-way and becomes a circular.
Power is controlled by every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the avenger of a citizen - can know all the secrets of power.
How can he maintain a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets?
It is true that Georg Simmel already said that the real secret is a meaningless secret (and a meaningless secret will never be revealed); it is also true that all information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is really a mysterious, meaningless secret because it is pulled from public life; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were meaningless secrets to him, means power to him.
WikiLeaks made no mistake about Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did something big to Clinton and Obama.
What are the consequences of this blow to the powers that be?
It is clear that in the future states will not be able to send sensitive information online - that would be equivalent to posting it on a poster posted on a street corner.
But it’s also pretty obvious that with current technology, it’s pointless to hope that you can keep messages secret over the phone.
There is nothing easier than to find out if and when a head of state traveled by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How will private and sensitive messages be kept secret in the future?
I know my prognosis is science fiction for the moment, and it’s fantastic, but I have to imagine government officials transporting themselves discreetly through uncontrollable routes carrying only those messages they know by heart, or rather, hiding precious information in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be preserved in unique copies in key-closed drawers: all in all, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving sideways, that is, backwards.
A century after wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet rehabilitated wire-based telegraph (telephone).
Videocassettes (analogues) allowed cinema lovers to shoot a movie step by step, moving it forward and backward, and uncovering all the secrets of assembly, while now CDs (digital) only allow them to jump chapters, that is, macroportions.
Via high-speed trains we arrive from Rome to Milan in three hours, while to travel by plane and transport, which includes we need three and a half hours.
It is therefore not uncommon for politics and communication techniques to revert to horse-drawn vehicles.
One final note.
At other times, the press tried to understand what had been orchestrated in secret at the embassy.
Now it is the embassies that are asking for confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France hacked its funding promises
A year after the Copenhagen Accord, it’s time to test the promise of fast-start or early-start financing made by developed countries.
And the great French hacks have been exposed
Under the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union has promised 7.2 billion euros for three years and France 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million euros per year).
At the launch of COP16, the EU pulled a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: a report detailing the actions of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation invaluable and valued for its real value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do them equally and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has mobilised 2.2 billion euros in 2010, putting it on track to deliver on its 7.2 billion euro pledge in 2012.
But if we look at the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
These funds are "new and additional" under the Copenhagen Accord to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without harming Public Aid for Development.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some member states, including France, blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission took 2009 as a reference: international funding has been preserved and it adds 150 million for three years of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment terms or with terms at the level of public aid for development.
France, on the other hand, considers that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words, there is no reference to expenditures of previous periods or to the global level of Public Aid for Development d'Aide publique au développement.
Specifically, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries can remain unchanged (or even decrease), to keep its commitment to funding “new and additional”...
Another crucial element is the division into gifts and loans.
There is no rule yet and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider 1x borrowed to be equal to 1x donated.
Evidently, this is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be substantiated for some investments that are profitable (often projects involving emission reductions, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , we should not understand it by virtue of our commitments, but as the price of a loan to a creditor country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France can only give such a justification: it is "complying" with its commitment of 420 million euros, of which 91.5% is a loan (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% is donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the world that uses such a loan.
Germany requested 46% of the donations, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) kept their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives 1 euro to make good on its promise, France only gives 10 centimes and considers this effort comparable.
What a beautiful piece of juggler!
To sum up, in its financing of the "fast start" France operates with double cheating: on the one hand, with the development of the stock over time, and on the other hand, with the real financial burden.
Although it spends only 36.1 million euros, it manages to convince that it spends 420 million euros "new and additional" in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the finance minister (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would member states continue to donate when they only need to lend?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The pre-financing chapter is only a small question mark, relatively short-lived, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not our case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to draw lessons from this first year of pre-financing.
First of all, France should announce a change in its way of keeping accounting records for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of compliance with its obligations and decency and fairness towards other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid a discussion about deposits in long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently under discussion): we will not escape the question of 'additionality' or how loans are booked.
France should change its position to become as progressive with these deposits as it is with others.
So everyone is putting their hope in the new environment minister, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who is coming to Cancun next week.
The surprise announcement of France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in discussions.
Pesticides that children ingest.
A 10-year-old child will one day ingest 81 different chemicals, according to a study published this Wednesday, from the Association of Future Generations (ex-Movement for the Rights and Preservation of Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value due to the low number of samples analysed, but are characteristic of the issue being processed", bought food commonly consumed in four meals and one light meal as a light snack for one child roughly ten years old in supermarkets in l'Oise and Paris between July and September.
These typical dishes, including official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as confectionery, were analyzed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are carcinogenic, possible or probable, and five are among the clear carcinogenic substances, as well as 37 substances that could act as interfering for the endocrine glands (PE), according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Center for Cancer Research.
“Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, we can well see in our research that the reality in consumer exposure to contaminants, perhaps carcinogenic, and/or PE is striking,” the association says.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk alone contain about ten résidences with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven to be certain carcinogens, as is the case with about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
Imported from Brazil, the apple, reported in the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same is true for green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, for which studies have found traces of powerful insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, minced meat steak, canned tuna, and even bun and chewing gum were laced with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water analysis revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
Salmon steak for dinner was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues discovered, and even analysis of the plastic plate used to heat food in the microwave failed to avoid analysis.
The final risk to consumers of this "cocktail of contaminants" is likely to be underestimated," the study concludes.
The Green Europe-Greens Association (EE-LV) has proposed to "face the emergency" by setting up a moratorium on pesticide use to stop the "increase in civilization diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) examined the status of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
